<article>
    <h1>What is an exit strat&#xAD;egy?</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201130/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-30"><time>2020-11-30</time></a>
        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>An exit strat­egy is how a start-up gets money out of the com­pany and how in­vestors can get a re­turn on the cap­i­tal they in­vested in it.</p>
    <p>Com­mon exit strate­gies in­clude go­ing pub­lic and fil­ing for an ini­tial pub­lic of­fer­ing (IPO), which means hav­ing the com­pany’s shares traded and owned pub­licly.</p>
    <p>For ex­am­ple, Sin­ga­pore-head­quar­tered Sea, which owns e-com­merce plat­form Shopee, listed on the New York Stock Ex­change in 2017.</p>
    <p>Mean­while, va­ca­tion rental mar­ket­place Airbnb, which was founded in 2008, is go­ing pub­lic in an IPO next month.</p>
    <p>Other start-ups may choose the ac­qui­si­tion or merger route. Au­ton­o­mous driv­ing start-up Zoox, for ex­am­ple, was ac­quired by on­line re­tailer Ama­zon ear­lier this year.</p>


